s speaks to and moves beyond the critical junctures in the study of Canadian literatures today. In the aftermath of the Truth and Reconciliation Commission and following Canada’s sesquicentennial, Land/Relations presents a collaborative effort at what Smaro Kamboureli and Larissa Lai call “counter-memory,” a collective effort to recognise “relationships that have always been”—between peoples, between humanity and other living forms, between us and the land—in an effort to avoid erasure, loss, and trauma. Twenty influential literary critics engage a variety of genres—essay, life writing, testament, polemic, poetry—to explore the ways Canadian cultural production has been shaped by social and historical relations and can be given new and various forms to decolonize the institutions associated with the creation of this country’s vision of Canadian literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian literaturexSocial aspects. 0aDecolonization in literature. 0aLand tenure in literature. 0aRace relations in literature. 4aIndigenous Studies. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh  a.  aArab.  aBlack.  aCanadian criticism.  aChinese Canadian.  aChris Lee.  aDina Al-Kassim.  aEileen Antone.  aErin Moure.  aFirst Nations.  aGothic.  aIndigeneity.  aIndigenous critical studies.  aIndigenous drama.  aIslamophobia.  aJennifer Henderson.  aJordan Abel.  aKarina Vernon.  aLen Findlay.  aLillian Allen.  aMargery Fee.  aMuslims.  aNative.  aPamela Mordecai.  aRinaldo Walcott.  aRita Wong.  aSedef Arat-Koç.  aSonnet L’Abbé.  aSophie McCall.  aTasha Hubbard.  aTransCanada project.  aTruth and Reconciliation.  aWarren Cariou.  aactivism.  abuffalo.  acolonial vio